segments.text: We are in the office of Nestor Valencia, the planning director for El Paso.
Nestor has taken time off to visit with us during his leave, for which I wish to thank him.
And I have a list of questions here, Nestor, that we might want to follow.
To the best of your ability, what do you remember was the first time that legislative authorization for planning occurred in El Paso?
Well, I think we need to go back to the George Kessler period, and the exact date of
authorization for legislation for planning in El Paso is, I don't know.
We can look it up.
Planning in El Paso has a long history.
It is undoubtedly a pioneer in the state of Texas that El Paso had planning long before any other city in Texas ever thought of having city planning.
We have to get a date on it.
Well, yeah, we're going to get some dates.
And it was a sort of a quirk of luck at somebody's expense of health, because as you remember, there's a Mr. George Kessler involved, who was a final architect.

He was immigrated, I think, from Germany to the United States at an early age, and became one of the most prominent planner-architects in the United States, I'd say, between the period of 1890 to 1920.
Mr. Kessler is
He is an author of many city planning documents in the United States, and he worked out of St. Louis.
As I remember, Jonathan Cunningham had his plan reproduced on the anniversary of the 1925 plan for El Paso.
We were fortunate to find
I would say about 50 or 60 copies of the original Kessler plant in the old city hall attic when the building was demolished.
So they were perfectly well preserved and intact and in their own pocket envelopes.
So they were in exceptional shape.
People bagged this with...
They were found about 1960.
And they were complete comprehensive plans that had come off the print shop but had never ever been touched or used.
Is there any chance of getting one of those for archives?
Probably not the original.
The original, unfortunately, the 40 or 50 originals were very poorly handled in that everybody was, not everybody, but people began to get copies and copies and they were distributed.
Unfortunately, they should have been kept for planning purposes.
I have an original copy in my office which is, you know, belongs to the plan.
I have reproduced the plan, I've republished it, a hundred copies of it, which is certainly not the same quality as the original, but nonetheless it's a
Oh, it's an effort to perpetuate the original Kessler plan or the 1925 plan in the city.
But you can certainly, you're welcome to one of the copies that we have reproduced.
But Kessler was sent to a place by his doctors to a drug client.
He was in ill health.
And he had visited El Paso from time to time and had encouraged friends in the community to begin looking at El Paso for the possibility of developing a master plan.
He encouraged a few friends and there were probably two reasons for Kessler to encourage his friends.
would like to be the consultant for El Paso at that time.
And secondly, he felt the professional need that a city like El Paso should have a master plan, regardless of whether he got hired or not.
I think Kessler was of the vintage whose primary concern was that the city could get a master plan underway and adopted by a mayor and council.
So what happened was a combination of both.
Mr. Kessler was was hired as a consultant and Mr. Kessler engineered the first city plant for El Paso.
He must have been hired around 1923 or 1924.
He was hired
There was a city plant commission established in El Paso in 1919.
And I think Kessler had already visited El Paso prior to that.
But at any rate, between 1919 and 1924, Kessler's major efforts were made to develop the master plant.
Just before he finished his plan, he died.

And so the city engineer, Walter E. Stockwell, Walter E. Stockwell was the key person to carry on all of Kessler's work through to completion, publish the plan, and get it adopted by the mayor's council as the official plan for the city.
Walter E. Stockwell picked it up from that point, I would say in 1824-25, a superior person who was the city plan engineer.
Down 1924 all the way up to probably 1952.
Is that right?
It's a long tenure, yeah.
He was an interesting person because he was planner-engineer.
Well, it's not unusual in the United States to have a plant arrangement as a combination of foliage and planting efforts.
But I think Walter was more of a planter at heart in that by 1930, well, the Plant Commission was already in operation, say, during the decade of the 20s, a lot of the decade.
There is also a Robert G. Report, which is a capital improvement program.
It's, I recall, headed by the Planning Commission in the 20s.
Some cities are just getting around to doing that now.
And we had official zoning adopted by the city in 1830.
So our first official zoning map, our first official...
zoning ordinances were in 1930.
That was my next question.
So, and right after Stockwell came, I fell off.
I had a hard time in the 50s in that my recollection of planning was Kessler, Stockwell, and then after Stockwell came, Wingo.
How do you spell it?
Just Wingo.
W-I-N-G-O.
Go ahead.
So after it was Wingo in the 50s, and then you were a little sketchy, you thought.
Well, I think after Wingo,
John Cunningham came and took over.
So that's... You don't remember the year of that?
1958, John came in, no, Cunningham came in 1957.
Probably about November of 57.
So I don't recall knowing of any other director of planning other than Wingle.
And then you took over in 1980.
How would you say that your style of directorship differs from Jonathan's?
That's a very difficult question.
It really is because John Cunningham's career in planning parallels mine in no question.
John was here a few months
I moved here and assumed the directorship of planning back in 57, and I was the first person he hired after he came to El Paso.
Of course, there was a lot of difference.
John was a director and I was a junior planning aide or some beginning slot in the planning department, but I was very fortunate to
be with Mr. Cunningham throughout his career in planning in El Paso.
There were only two of you initially?
In planning?
No.
We had a staff of, back then we had probably a staff of about 22.
When he got here.
Which was a very comfortable staff for the size of the city and the complexity of the job back then.
John came here probably in November of 1957, and I came on board in February of 1958, just a few months after he got here.

I was willing to relate that the difference is that he was already a professional planner, director, who had been in Spokane working, I believe he was director of planning, and had headed the Puget Sound Council of Governments.
So, I am
I interned with John Cunningham.
My first ten years was working with Cunningham and then we, since the time that I started
There was only one year from 1969 to 1970 that I was away doing work for the Council of Governments.
Then back in 71 and 72, I was away in Costa Rica doing work.
And back in 19... What sort of thing did you do in Costa Rica?
City and regional planning, consulting work for the government of Costa Rica.
The federal government of Costa Rica.
Yeah.
But I was also assistant director of planning for the city of El Paso in between...
Somewhere in 1970, I was assistant director of planning for a while.
Then I became urban coordinator between 72 and 73.
And between 73 and 75, I was away from the office because I was assistant director.
executive assistant to Mayor Hervey.
From 75 to 77, I was assistant to Don Henderson.
And then from 77 to 1980, I was... Don Henderson was ex-mayor, ex-pro.
And then between 1977 and 1980, I was director of federal branch for the city.
Pardon me.
And then 1980, I took over the planet.
So it's kind of been sporadic, but in the same general area.
Mm-hmm.
One question, though.
To answer the question of, you know, the style of being .
It's difficult to answer because
At least for ten solid years, we worked very closely.
I worked very closely with Cunningham.
And for the next additional seven or eight years, we were in constant communication with local government.
His style of planning was very

i would say very classical it's a classical type of planning very strong on the principles in planning city planning very articulate man before the mayor council who was able to to defend planning's positioning
not necessarily on feeling or on the politics of the day, but on true professional framework.
Yeah.
I think John Cunningham and I have the same approach to planning.
We feel that planning is more than just the physical development of a plan.
We happen to both think that planning in any city, specifically in El Paso, is more of a policy recommending department and not necessarily a line department.
Planning should be closely
related to the office of the mayor and there should be a considerable amount of interchange between the mayor and the department of planning.
John felt very strong about this.
He felt that of all of the departments in the city, planning was the focal point for

for policy formulation and to give direction to the mayor and city council on matters which involve the community as opposed to being a process, a processing network, a machine that would process subdivisions and so on.
I feel very strongly about that.

I think engineering has its place, public works has its place, building inspection, traffic and transportation, and the very nature of planning puts planning in perhaps a more advantageous position over these other departments in terms of a global
or a comprehensive view of the city or understanding of the city.
Going back to comprehensive planning, El Paso has a long history of comprehensive citywide planning.
And I'm wondering, is there any specific periodic review of El Paso's comprehensive plan?
Does it occur annually or every five years or anything of that nature?
We try to keep on a five to seven year revisit of the master plan.
We are right now in the process of
are upgrading our plan this year and next year.
It's been about five years and five or six years now, so we are setting aside some monies for consulting work, some monies this year and next year,
both local funds and community development funds to upgrade our plan.
We're looking at it differently.
We want to emphasize more or less a strategy plan rather than a 20-year company plan.
Who will be doing that work?
Well, planning.
The Department of Planning is going to have to
find time and ways and means of allowing some of the people internally to get out of the fast lanes and work on the plan 100%.
If I had 100 people instead of 40 or such, we could still be on the fast track, every one of us.
by just simply doing work that is either required, requested, or needed, which we have done.
There's two or three baskets, that which we would like to do, that which needs to be done, and that which is necessary to do now.
for political reasons, for the issues of the day, your priorities are sometimes set for you.
So there are three or four flavors of projects that we can get involved in.
And one of them is find enough time to do a company's plan.
Of course, we're going to get some money, $100,000 for consulting.
I see.
You will have outside consultants.
Oh, yeah.
There's no way that we can do it internally.
And even at that, even with the small amount of money that we're going to assemble, and with all the effort that we can muster internally, it's going to be a very skimpy revamp from this point.
I realize that.
You know, planning, as I was saying, planning in El Paso is no different from other parts of the United States and proud.
The only difference is that we have a longer history in planning than most cities.

One of the things that you find different in El Paso from other cities, and maybe not strikingly different in Texas, but certainly throughout the United States, is the fact that we don't have urban renewal.
never had it and we probably won't have it where eminent domain plays a big role in redevelopment.
Voters defeated that twice already and I don't think that there stands a chance to put it on the ballot again for the next 50 years.
That's political normal.
So

While other cities throughout the United States were going through urban renewal process in the late 50s and early 60s, El Paso was sort of a by itself city doing what it could in the planning process without any federal assistance whatsoever.
It was not until the good old 701 came through that
that we got any federal assistance planning.

Prior to that, it was a relatively simple process of planning the neighborhood, classic neighborhood planning, the classic master plan, the classic land use, with little or no federal funding or interference or involvement.
As time went on and
and community development came into play and revenue sharing and we went public transit and we were beginning to get more and more federal involvement, the planning process became more complex.
We now have to, you know, coordinate a lot of the issues with other agencies, which is good.
The Highway Department, Community Development, HUD.
And now it is more, it is not, it has become a little more complex because of
of the natural things that have occurred throughout the United States.
The council of governments prior to 1965 didn't exist in any way.
The regional councils of government, then the camps program came to be, and which evolved into something else.
Well, at any rate, the council government's movement in El Paso began in 1965.
And so, you know, other issues such as the Chamizal settlement had, I think, a very significant impact on the planning of El Paso.
For one thing, the Chamizal settlement brought about enough
federal assistance to update our master plan.
That was one of the byproducts of the international treaty between the United States and Mexico, and we got some money to upgrade our plan.
And we did.
Do you remember how much it was?
I'm going to guess, but I think it was about $200,000.
which then was a whole lot of money.
Oh yeah, sure.
Big bucks.
But the Chummy's Isle was probably the biggest impact in terms of, you know, the planning process.
Tax increment financing,
is important, although very recent.
We now have a tax-included financing district.
That's about it.
I think we have a viable zoning ordinance.
We have a viable subdivision processing system.
We have ETJ jurisdiction.
We wish the heck we had more enforcement of zoning and subdivision activity, but we don't.
But that's being here and there.
I think the city has enjoyed some very excellent support by previous administrations.
in mayors and councils, but would you care to point out any individuals by name?
Sure.
Peter DeWitter, 69, 69-71.
Judson Williams, very strong mayor and very strong supporter of planning, 63 to probably 69.
Raymond Theus was a very strong supporter and is still a very strong supporter of city planning.
How did he spell his last name?
T-E-L-L-E-S. Raymond Theus was subsequently an ambassador to Costa Rica in the United States, and is now living in El Paso.
So we've had Theus, we have had Judson Williams, Peter DeWetter,
We have had Don Henderson who was a strong supporter of City Planning.
His period was between 75 and 77.
We certainly have had excellent support, super excellent support by now Mayor Jonathan Rogers who came into office in
Well, he came to us in 1981 and he is a very strong believer and a very strong believer to uphold the decisions of the city plan commission.
Strongly supports plan commission decisions at the council level.
seldom, and I don't recall one time that the mayor himself has ever gone against the workers in the last four years.
That's remarkable.
It is.
He knows real estate, he knows development, and he knows about income.
So I think El Paso has enjoyed some excellent administrations
as far as political support is concerned.
What about the relationship of the city to state government?
Has there been much, in a way, of benefits from the state or otherwise, from the point of view of planning?
Not really.
other than working very closely with the state highway department.
And there has been some periods of time that we have worked with the Governor's Office of Economic Development related to border conferences and border regional commissions and that sort of thing.
The state is very much not
involved.
